title: Add ACP (Agent Client Protocol) support for coder subagents
---
Problem
Clawq's coder subagents (delegate, background_task_enqueue, etc.) currently use custom integrations for each runner (codex, claude, kimi, opencode, cursor). There is no standardized protocol for editor/IDE integration with these agents.

Why this matters
ACP (Agent Client Protocol) is an emerging standard from Zed Industries and JetBrains that standardizes communication between code editors/IDEs and coding agents - similar to how LSP standardized language server integration. Supporting ACP would:
- Enable clawq subagents to work with any ACP-compatible editor
- Reduce per-runner integration overhead
- Position clawq in the emerging ACP ecosystem
- Allow remote agent hosting scenarios

Acceptance criteria
- Research ACP spec at https://agentclientprotocol.com/get-started/introduction and document integration requirements
- Implement ACP client capability (clawq acts as ACP client to spawn/control agents)
- Local agent support via JSON-RPC over stdio
- Remote agent support via HTTP/WebSocket (optional initially)
- Tool calls, file system access, and terminal operations work via ACP
- At least one existing runner migrated to ACP as proof of concept
- Documentation updated to explain ACP mode

Notes
- ACP reuses MCP JSON representations where possible
- Default text format is Markdown
- See also: existing MCP support in clawq (P1.M3.E1.T001)
- This is a larger feature - consider breaking into phases
- Related to B129 (/delegate slash command)